# Git Attributes - Line Ending Configuration
# This ensures consistent line endings across Windows and Linux

# ============================================================================
# Default Behavior
# ============================================================================

# Auto-normalize all text files to LF on commit
# This prevents CRLF from being committed to the repository
* text=auto eol=lf

# ============================================================================
# Scripts (CRITICAL - enforce LF)
# ============================================================================

# Shell scripts MUST use LF (required by bash/sh on Linux)
*.sh text eol=lf

# PowerShell scripts use LF (PowerShell 3+ supports LF on Windows)
*.ps1 text eol=lf

# ============================================================================
# Documentation and Config Files
# ============================================================================

# Markdown files
*.md text eol=lf

# YAML configuration
*.yml text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf

# Text files
*.txt text eol=lf

# Config examples
*.example text eol=lf

# ============================================================================
# Binary Files (do not normalize)
# ============================================================================

# Model files (GGUF format)
*.gguf binary

# Executables and libraries
*.exe binary
*.dll binary
*.so binary
*.dylib binary
*.bin binary

# Archives
*.zip binary
*.tar binary
*.gz binary
*.tgz binary
*.7z binary

# Images
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.ico binary
*.bmp binary

# ============================================================================
# Notes
# ============================================================================
#
# Why LF everywhere?
# 1. Shell scripts (.sh) require LF - they fail with CRLF on Linux
# 2. Modern PowerShell (v3+) works fine with LF on Windows
# 3. Git diffs are cleaner without CRLF noise
# 4. Consistency across all platforms
#
# This file ensures:
# - Repository always stores LF
# - Windows users can check out with LF (recommended)
# - Cross-platform development works seamlessly
#
# If you need CRLF locally on Windows:
#   git config core.autocrlf false  (recommended - use LF everywhere)
#   git config core.autocrlf true   (converts to CRLF on checkout)
#
